title: Annual Rate of Spotted Owl Population Decline in 11 Northwest Study Areas
name: Annual Rate of Spotted Owl Population Decline in 11 Northwest Study Areas
description:
The northern spotted owl was listed as a threatened species in 1990. 
Scientists are studying owl population changes at 11 sites in the Pacific Northwest. 

Based on data consolidated from the 11 study areas, the spotted owl population is declining at a rate of 2.9 percent a year.

The rate of decline is faster in the northern part of the owls' range, where invasive Barred Owls have been present longest. 

In four study areas in the southern part of the owl's range (labeled TYE, KLA, CAS, and HUP on the map) populations were either stable, or declines were within the data's range of error.

author.source: Data was adapted from Population Demography of Northern Spotted Owls, Forsman et. al.
